The terms are confusing.  It's a "coldkey wallet" in Bittensor, as opposed to a "hotkey wallet" -- the coldkey is where you can transfer TAO to and from, and you need to maintain a minimum existential balance of 500 RAO in there to keep it functional.  The hotkey (or hotkeys, if you set up more than one to be controlled by a particular coldkey) is where rewards accrue (incentive for miners, dividends for validators).
There is a very good document in the help-forum regarding "Best Practices for Key Management": https://discord.com/channels/799672011265015819/1199369618150670376/1199369618150670376

"Hot wallet" and "cold wallet" are general blockchain/crypto terms for "a wallet interface that is always connected to the Internet, like a browser extension" and "a wallet interface that is usually *not* connected to the Internet, except for the very specific instances in which the user needs to authorize a transaction, like a Ledger or Polkadot Vault device".

I say "wallet **interface**" because it's a common misconception, especially among new users, that the "wallet" actually contains tokens (so, for example, they think that they can prevent scammers from accessing their assets by deleting the application).  But this isn't true.
